e is competition for that time spent.\r\n\r\n<strong>We have found a way to reach our users every time they pick up their phone!</strong>\r\n<h2><a href=\"http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/AdoraAdExamples.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright  wp-image-134\" src=\"http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/AdoraAdExamples.jpg\" alt=\"AdoraAdExamples\" width=\"421\" height=\"621\" /></a>Second Point: Real Estate</h2>\r\nThe next problem advertisers find when it comes to mobile, especially on phones, is the amount of space on the screen they get to deliver their message.\r\n\r\nThere are two popular ways of advertising on mobile:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Text Ads</li>\r\n	<li>Banner Ads</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThen you have the Facebook Sponsored Stories, and Twitter Promoted Tweets. Both of these are, in most cases, performing much better than Text and Banner Ads.\r\n\r\nWith the advent of rich media more formats are becoming popular. New applications for traditional advertising are popping up; video, call to actions, slides, and a technique that many brands are trying - subtle advertising - where the brand or product is subtly featured and not featured all at the same time.\r\n\r\nStill with 99% of the advertising opportunities out there the user is using their device to do something other than look at advertising... And those ads have become a turn off. Not only are they a turn off but they often are not maximizing the real estate - not using the entire screen.\r\n\r\nOur ads will use the entire screen, we will also make it 100% clear that every time they see an ad they are helping someone in need. This helps connect brands to users with a totally different mindset and charge to that interaction.','The opportunity for MAD Men (and women!)','','inherit','open','open','','119-revision-v1','','','2014-05-05 13:29:11','2014-05-05 13:29:11','',119,'http://getadora.com/119-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(137,1,'2014-05-05 13:29:36','2014-05-05 13:29:36','We want to more clearly spell out why we feel our ad is going to be the absolute best ad opportunity for brands and the ad agencies that manage them.\r\n<h2>First Point: Reach</h2>\r\n<a href=\"http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/TimeSpentUS.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-120\" src=\"http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/TimeSpentUS.jpg\" alt=\"TimeSpentUS\" width=\"324\" height=\"321\" /></a>Mobile advertising is the fastest growing sub-sector in the advertising world, and for good reason.\r\n\r\nIf you look at the \'Share of Time Spent per Day with Major Media by US adults, 2010-2014\' you see a trend. First take a look at the change from TV to Digital from 2010-2014. Then take a look inside the digital breakdown, specifically the mobile and online share. It is clear that mobile is where the eyes are and where more are going.\r\n\r\nThis trend will only continue with greater saturation of smartphones, tablets, wearables and who knows what will come out next, but you can be sure it\'s mobile.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/TimeSpentonMobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright  wp-image-126\" src=\"http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/TimeSpentonMobile.jpg\" alt=\"TimeSpentonMobile\" width=\"335\" height=\"310\" /></a>Everyone is trying to figure out how to use mobile to advertise, it is not an easy problem to crack. Think about how you use your phone. First when you pick up your phone you are going to do one of a few things: make or answer a call, search for something or some location, play a game, check a notification, respond to that notification (text, Facebook, tweet, etc)\r\n\r\nSee as an advertiser or an app there is no guarantee that the user is going to interact with your app, utility, or browser based website. There is competition for that time spent.\r\n\r\n<strong>We have found a way to reach our users every time they pick up their phone!</strong>\r\n<h2><a href=\"http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/AdoraAdExamples.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright  wp-image-134\" src=\"http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/AdoraAdExamples.jpg\" alt=\"AdoraAdExamples\" width=\"390\" height=\"575\" /></a>Second Point: Real Estate</h2>\r\nThe next problem advertisers find when it comes to mobile, especially on phones, is the amount of space on the screen they get to deliver their message.\r\n\r\nThere are two popular ways of advertising on mobile:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Text Ads</li>\r\n	<li>Banner Ads</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThen you have the Facebook Sponsored Stories, and Twitter Promoted Tweets. Both of these are, in most cases, performing much better than Text and Banner Ads.\r\n\r\nWith the advent of rich media more formats are becoming popular. New applications for traditional advertising are popping up; video, call to actions, slides, and a technique that many brands are trying - subtle advertising - where the brand or product is subtly featured and not featured all at the same time.\r\n\r\nStill with 99% of the advertising opportunities out there the user is using their device to do something other than look at advertising... And those ads have become a turn off. Not only are they a turn off but they often are not maximizing the real estate - not using the entire screen.\r\n\r\nOur ads will use the entire screen, we will also make it 100% clear that every time they see an ad they are helping someone in need. This helps connect brands to users with a totally different mindset and charge to that interaction.','The opportunity for MAD Men (and women!)','','inherit','open','open','','119-revision-v1','','','2014-05-05 13:29:36','2014-05-05 13:29:36','',119,'http://getadora.com/119-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(138,1,'2014-05-05 13:37:03','2014-05-05 13:37:03','We want to more clearly spell out why we feel our ad is going to be the absolute best ad opportunity for brands and the ad agencies that manage them.\r\n<h2>First Point: Reach</h2>\r\n<a href=\"http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/TimeSpentUS.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-120\" src=\"http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/TimeSpentUS.jpg\" alt=\"TimeSpentUS\" width=\"324\" height=\"321\" /></a>Mobile advertising is the fastest growing sub-sector in the advertising world, and for good reason.\r\n\r\nIf you look at the \'Share of Time Spent per Day with Major Media by US adults, 2010-2014\' you see a trend. First take a look at the change from TV to Digital from 2010-2014. Then take a look inside the digital breakdown, specifically the mobile and online share. It is clear that mobile is where the eyes are and where more are going.\r\n\r\nThis trend will only continue with greater saturation of smartphones, tablets, wearables and who knows what will come out next, but you can be sure it\'s mobile.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/TimeSpentonMobile.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright  wp-image-126\" src=\"http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/TimeSpentonMobile.jpg\" alt=\"TimeSpentonMobile\" width=\"335\" height=\"310\" /></a>Everyone is trying to figure out how to use mobile to advertise, it is not an easy problem to crack. Think about how you use your phone. First when you pick up your phone you are going to do one of a few things: make or answer a call, search for something or some location, play a game, check a notification, respond to that notification (text, Facebook, tweet, etc)\r\n\r\nSee as an advertiser or an app there is no guarantee that the user is going to interact with your app, utility, or browser based website. There is competition for that time spent.\r\n\r\n<strong>We have found a way to reach our users every time they pick up their phone!</strong>\r\n<h2><a href=\"http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/AdoraAdExamples.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright  wp-image-134\" src=\"http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/AdoraAdExamples.jpg\" alt=\"AdoraAdExamples\" width=\"390\" height=\"575\" /></a>Second Point: Real Estate</h2>\r\nThe next problem advertisers find when it comes to mobile, especially on phones, is the amount of space on the screen they get to deliver their message.\r\n\r\nThere are two popular ways of advertising on mobile:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Text Ads</li>\r\n	<li>Banner Ads</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThen you have the Facebook Sponsored Stories, and Twitter Promoted Tweets. Both of these are, in most cases, performing much better than Text and Banner Ads.\r\n\r\nWith the advent of rich media more formats are becoming popular. New applications for traditional advertising are popping up; video, call to actions, slides, and a technique that many brands are trying - subtle advertising - where the brand or product is subtly featured and not featured all at the same time.\r\n\r\nStill with 99% of the advertising opportunities out there the user is using their device to do something other than look at advertising... And those ads have become a turn off. Not only are they a turn off but they often are not maximizing the real estate - not using the entire screen.\r\n<h2>Third Point: A Cause</h2>\r\nOur ads will use the entire screen, we will also make it 100% clear that every time they see an ad they are helping someone in need.\r\n\r\nWe want to make users and brands partners in the effort to get funding to charities.\r\n\r\nBy doing this we put these two parties on the same side, on the same team. This changes the way our users look at the ads we deliver, it encourages brand loyalty, even possibly adoration...','The opportunity for MAD Men (and women!)','','inherit','open','open','','119-revision-v1','','','2014-05-05 13:37:03','2014-05-05 13:37:03','',119,'http://getadora.com/119-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(139,5,'2014-05-06 14:01:53','2014-05-06 14:01:53','<h2> Adora Mobile Advertising Report: May 2014</h2>\r\nAs we have been preparing and researching the Adora app project we needed to know what the landscape was for mobile advertising.\r\n\r\nOver the last 3 months we\'ve done a great deal of research and while ad rates change constantly we have a fair grasp on current rates and trends.\r\n<h2>Types of Ads</h2>\r\nAs mobile is the fastest growing segment of information use by the public it\'s reasonable that advertisers are following the eyes.\r\n\r\n<strong>Text based ads</strong> like the Google ads you see when you execute a Google search are still a main stay. There are also text based Banner ads.\r\n\r\n<strong>Banner ads</strong> are those nice slim strips of advertising you see at the top and bottom of apps and web pages. They are quickly becoming yesterdays news, the Yahoo ad network is already phasing them out. The only way they are staying relevant at all is through the innovative use of rich media techniques.\r\n\r\n<strong>Embedded</strong> in app ads like Facebook Sponsored Stories and Twitter Promoted Tweets are examples of this type of ad.\r\n\r\nThen we have the new <strong>Subtlety Techniques</strong> that we are seeing on Instagram and through the use of short videos like Vine. Here is an example of brand subtlety in a youtube video:\r\n<iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/2lvRv2mnYLU\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe>\r\n\r\nThen we start to get into larger formats, <strong>full screen ads and full screen video players</strong> with interactive options. These must pop up or be part of a loading screen for apps, sites, or utilities to use these full screen ads. They are great use of real estate but some of the most annoying to users.\r\n<a href=\"http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/MobileAdvertisingExamples.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter  wp-image-140\" src=\"http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/MobileAdvertisingExamples.jpg\" alt=\"MobileAdvertisingExamples\" width=\"562\" height=\"2684\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nReferences:\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><strong>General Mobile CPM</strong>\r\n<a title=\"Top Performing CPM Zones\" href=\"http://buysellads.com/buy/leaderboard/id/17/soldout/1/ch/-1\" target=\"_blank\">Buy Sell Ads Leaderboard\r\n</a><a title=\"What Are Average CPM Rates in 2014?\" href=\"http://monetizepros.com/blog/2014/average-cpm-rates/\" target=\"_blank\">MonetizePros Average CPM Rates 2014\r\n</a><a title=\"What Is an Average Banner CPM?\" href=\"http://www.ehow.com/info_12200588_average-banner-cpm.html\" target=\"_blank\">eHow - What Is an Average Banner CPM?</a><a title=\"What Are Average CPM Rates in 2014?\" href=\"http://monetizepros.com/blog/2014/average-cpm-rates/\" target=\"_blank\">\r\n</a><a title=\"The Average CPM Rates for Mobile Advertising\" href=\"http://smallbusiness.chron.com/average-cpm-rates-mobile-advertising-72201.html\" target=\"_blank\">Chron Small Business - The Average CPM Rates for Mobile Advertising\r\n</a><a title=\"2014 Forecasts: Global Ad Dollars Surge, Driven By Mobile, Social\" href=\"http://http://www.adexchanger.com/agencies/2014-forecasts-global-ad-dollars-surge-driven-by-mobile-social/\" target=\"_blank\">Ad Exchanger - 2014 Forecasts: Global Ad Dollars Surge, Driven By Mobile, Social\r\n</a><a title=\"The Mobile Ad Network Roundup\" href=\"http://blog.apptopia.com/the-mobile-ad-network-rundown/\" target=\"_blank\">Apptopia - The Mobile Ad Network Roundup</a></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><strong>Facebook &amp; Twitter CPM Resources\r\n</strong><a title=\"Know Your Facebook Ad Rates: CPM and Cost Per Page Like by Placement\" href=\"http://www.jonloomer.com/2014/04/28/facebook-ad-rates-placement/\" target=\"_blank\">Jon Loomer - Know Your Facebook Ad Rates: CPM and Cost Per Page Like by Placement\r\n</a><a title=\"Facebook Mobile App Install Ads Capture Revenue, Drive Installs\" href=\"http://http://www.adexchanger.com/mobile/facebook-mobile-app-install-ads-capture-revenue-drive-installs/\" target=\"_blank\">Ad Exchanger - Facebook Mobile App Install Ads Capture Revenue, Drive Installs\r\n</a><a title=\"Hey Twitter, Your Ads Are Even Worse Than Facebook\'s — Here\'s The Data\" href=\"http://https://finance.yahoo.com/news/hey-twitter-ads-even-worse-195743153.html\" target=\"_blank\">Yahoo - Hey Twitter, Your Ads Are Even Worse Than Facebook\'s — Here\'s The Data\r\n</a><a title=\"Twitter Investment Thesis\" href=\"http://www.slideshare.net/augustinefou/investment-thesis-twitter-by-augustine-fou-april-2014\" target=\"_blank\">Slideshare - Twitter Investment Thesis</a></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><strong>Mobile Video CPM Resources</strong>\r\n<a title=\"Online Video Advertising Moves Front and Center\" href=\"http://www.emarketer.com/Article/Online-Video-Advertising-Moves-Front-Center/1009886\" target=\"_blank\">eMarketer - Online Video Advertising Moves Front and Center</a> (Digital Video Ad Spending, 2011-2017)\r\n<a title=\"3 Reasons Brands Shouldn’t be Surprised Online Video Ads Out-Price TV Spots\" href=\"https://smallbusiness.yahoo.com/advisor/3-reasons-brands-shouldn-t-surprised-online-video-154514773.html\" target=\"_blank\">Yahoo - 3 Reasons Brands Shouldn’t be Surprised Online Video Ads Out-Price TV Spots</a></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><strong>Trends\r\n</strong><a title=\"Four mobile advertising trends to look out for in 2014\" href=\"http://http://www.theguardian.com/media-network/ebuzzing-partner-zone/mobile-advertising-trends-2014\" target=\"_blank\">The Guardian - </a><a title=\"Four mobile advertising trends to look out for in 2014\" href=\"http://http://www.theguardian.com/media-network/ebuzzing-partner-zone/mobile-advertising-trends-2014\" target=\"_blank\">Four mobile advertising trends to look out for in 2014</a><a title=\"Four mobile advertising trends to look out for in 2014\" href=\"http://http://www.theguardian.com/media-network/ebuzzing-partner-zone/mobile-advertising-trends-2014\" target=\"_blank\">\r\nAppFlood - </a><a title=\"10 reasons why your mobile app eCPM is decreasing\" href=\"http://appflood.co