tect your information and remain vigilant in its defence.\n\nEven when we can count on companies to protect our information, we can’t always count on them not to sell that information to third parties. We all hate it when our information gets sold and we start getting spammed by third parties.\n\nSo here is our commitment to all of you - We are committed to safeguarding your data and promise to never share your contact information with third parties - period.','Privacy vs Data','','inherit','open','open','','372-autosave-v1','','','2014-05-16 08:57:51','2014-05-16 08:57:51','',372,'http://getadora.com/372-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(375,1,'2014-05-16 08:57:57','2014-05-16 08:57:57','Just to be clear there is no fight here, no decision here, not at Adora.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"A love for Jim Collins\" href=\"http://getadora.com/love-jim-collins/\">Jim Collins</a> is famous for the book ‘Good to Great’ but in an earlier book, ‘Built to Last’ he spoke of a decision making paradigm that we like to follow:\r\n<blockquote>\"The genius of the AND vs. the tyranny of the OR\"</blockquote>\r\nWe refuse to believe that we have to sacrifice privacy in order to use data to make a great product. We will never use any data in a way that compromises anyones privacy.\r\n\r\n<strong>Data</strong>\r\n\r\nPrivacy concerns are no longer in the background for those who use sites like Facebook and Twitter or tools provided by Google.\r\n\r\nThe problem with so many of these sites, tools and utilities lies with the fact that they do not work well, if at all, without a great deal of data. It has become the price we pay for cheap or free services.\r\n\r\nWe here at Adora are no different in the need for data. Information about who you are helps us direct useful and even desired offers and ads to you. Our app is designed to engage users. With each engagement, we will get better at choosing and presenting those ads which are most relevant to you. Not only will this provide more value to you, the user, but it will also add value to our charity partners. Every improvement will translate into additional dollars going to charities who serve the causes you care most about. If we cannot do this we, and you, are not valuable to the advertisers who we need to fund our good works.\r\n\r\nThe main difference between our motivations and those of others like those we’ve mentioned above - we aim to do as much good as we can.\r\n\r\n<strong>Privacy</strong>\r\n\r\nGoogle’s unofficial motto - “Don’t Be Evil”\r\n\r\nThis isn’t a very inspiring motto, in it there leaves a great deal of grey area left to interpretation. Where is the evil line?\r\n\r\nIn the age of big data, we need more than a vague commitment of not being evil. Companies need to take significant steps to protect your information and remain vigilant in its defence.\r\n\r\nEven when we can count on companies to protect our information, we can’t always count on them not to sell that information to third parties. We all hate it when our information gets sold and we start getting spammed by third parties.\r\n\r\nSo here is our commitment to all of you - We are committed to safeguarding your data and promise to never share your contact information with third parties - period.','Privacy vs Data','','inherit','open','open','','372-revision-v1','','','2014-05-16 08:57:57','2014-05-16 08:57:57','',372,'http://getadora.com/372-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(376,1,'2014-05-16 09:13:38','2014-05-16 09:13:38','','Privacy','','inherit','open','open','','privacy','','','2014-05-16 09:13:38','2014-05-16 09:13:38','',372,'http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Privacy.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(377,4,'2014-04-25 09:25:36','2014-04-25 09:25:36','For the past few months we\'ve been working on this idea, one that just might help a lot of people, but we didn\'t have a name.\r\n\r\nUntil today.\r\n\r\nWe are pleased to introduce you to <strong>Adora.</strong>\r\n\r\n<a title=\"The Story Behind a Name\" href=\"http://getadora.com/story-behind-name/\">Read more about how we came to be named so well.</a>','Welcome to Adora','','publish','open','open','','welcome-adora','','\nhttp://getadora.com/story-behind-name/','2014-05-16 11:15:24','2014-05-16 11:15:24','',0,'http://getadora.com/?p=377',0,'post','',0),(378,1,'2014-05-16 09:25:36','2014-05-16 09:25:36','For the past few months we\'ve been working on this idea, one that just might help a lot of people, but we didn\'t have a name.\r\n\r\nUntil today.\r\n\r\nWe are pleased to introduce you to Adora.\r\n\r\nRead more about how we came to be named so well.','Welcome to Adora','','inherit','open','open','','377-revision-v1','','','2014-05-16 09:25:36','2014-05-16 09:25:36','',377,'http://getadora.com/377-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(379,1,'2014-05-16 09:27:13','2014-05-16 09:27:13','For the past few months we\'ve been working on this idea, one that just might help a lot of people, but we didn\'t have a name.\r\n\r\nUntil today.\r\n\r\nWe are pleased to introduce you to <strong>Adora.</strong>\r\n\r\nRead more about how we came to be named so well.','Welcome to Adora','','inherit','open','open','','377-revision-v1','','','2014-05-16 09:27:13','2014-05-16 09:27:13','',377,'http://getadora.com/377-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(380,1,'2014-05-16 09:33:41','2014-05-16 09:33:41','','ColorLogo','','inherit','open','open','','colorlogo','','','2014-05-16 09:33:41','2014-05-16 09:33:41','',377,'http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/ColorLogo.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(381,3,'2014-04-26 11:10:00','2014-04-26 11:10:00','In the beginning, we worked without a real name, just an acronym, so when we finally turned to try and find a name for our venture, we struggled as nothing quite seemed to fit.\r\n\r\nIn late April we took the few ideas we did have and put them to our friends and family in the form of a survey, but even then many stated that the right name did not seem to be on the list.\r\n\r\nThe name “Adora” came about during a conversation with my brother when we discussed the app idea and I asked him if he had any name suggestions. We started brainstorming and he began throwing out ideas, such as “Ad-ittude”, which is one of the names I remember he mentioned. From that thought I said “Ad-ora”. We recognized this had some similarity  to the name “Pandora” and it made sense, as our concept seemed to be like an “ad” version of Pandora, the automated music recommendation service. Our app will be an ad recommendation service with the single mission of delivering ads you’ll love. Rather than enjoy music, in return we all get to enjoy the great feeling of doing good because of the money generated for charities by using the app.\r\n\r\nAs we\'ve done with every other name idea, we looked at it from all directions. I speak fluent Spanish, so Latin-based words feel at home with me. Because of this I knew that Adora was a feminine name. This made sense as we all know the gentler sex is more giving, loving and full of charity.\r\n\r\nLater, as we researched the name, we found that \'adora\' means “gift”; “beloved”; “adored” and is of Greek, Old German, and Latin origin. The name is also associated with the root word to “love” which is “adorare” in Latin. For example, “adora” in Portuguese (a latin-based language) means “love.”\r\n\r\nThis meaning fits not only perfectly with the charity focus of the app, which can be described as providing “gifts” to charity motivated by “love”, but also the fact that our mission is to deliver only ads that you will “love” based on the app’s ability to learn over time from user activity which ads are relevant and desirable.\r\n\r\nThere is not much more to tell about the discovery of our name, but as we have shared it with others, everyone has fallen in love with both the name and the meaning. We invite you to do the same. Join us in our passion to love our fellow man.','The Story Behind a Name','','publish','open','open','','story-behind-name','','','2014-06-18 09:12:58','2014-06-18 09:12:58','',0,'http://getadora.com/?p=381',0,'post','',0),(382,1,'2014-05-16 09:45:27','2014-05-16 09:45:27','The name “Adora” came about during a conversation with my brother when we discussed the app idea and I asked him if he had any name suggestions. We started brainstorming and he began throwing out ideas, such as, “Ad-ittude” which is one of the names I remember he mentioned. From that thought I said “Ad-ora”, which was meant to be a spin-off of “Pandora” because our concept seemed to be like an “ad” version of Pandora, the automated music recommendation service. Our app will be an ad recommendation service with the single mission of delivering ads you’ll love (we may not want to present it as a knock off of pandora?…).\r\n\r\nLater we discovered that the name adora is a feminine name and actually means “gift”; “beloved”; “adored” and is of Greek, Old German, and Latin origin. The name is also associated with the root word to “love” which is “adorare” in Latin. For example, “adora” in Portuguese (a latin-based language) means “love.”\r\n\r\nThis meaning fits not only perfectly with the charity focus of the app, which can be described as providing “gifts” to charity motivated by “love”, but also the fact that our mission is to deliver only ads that you will “love” based on the app’s ability to learn over time from user activity which ads are relevant and desirable (we may not want to promise this yet?…)','The Story Behind a Name','','inherit','open','open','','381-revision-v1','','','2014-05-16 09:45:27','2014-05-16 09:45:27','',381,'http://getadora.com/381-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(383,1,'2014-05-16 10:11:54','2014-05-16 10:11:54','When we finally turned to try and find a name for our venture we struggled as nothing quite fit.\r\n\r\nWe\r\n\r\nThe name “Adora” came about during a conversation with my brother when we discussed the app idea and I asked him if he had any name suggestions. We started brainstorming and he began throwing out ideas, such as, “Ad-ittude” which is one of the names I remember he mentioned. From that thought I said “Ad-ora”, which was meant to be a spin-off of “Pandora” because our concept seemed to be like an “ad” version of Pandora, the automated music recommendation service. Our app will be an ad recommendation service with the single mission of delivering ads you’ll love (we may not want to present it as a knock off of pandora?…).\r\n\r\nLater we discovered that the name adora is a feminine name and actually means “gift”; “beloved”; “adored” and is of Greek, Old German, and Latin origin. The name is also associated with the root word to “love” which is “adorare” in Latin. For example, “adora” in Portuguese (a latin-based language) means “love.”\r\n\r\nThis meaning fits not only perfectly with the charity focus of the app, which can be described as providing “gifts” to charity motivated by “love”, but also the fact that our mission is to deliver only ads that you will “love” based on the app’s ability to learn over time from user activity which ads are relevant and desirable (we may not want to promise this yet?…)','The Story Behind a Name','','inherit','open','open','','381-revision-v1','','','2014-05-16 10:11:54','2014-05-16 10:11:54','',381,'http://getadora.com/381-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(384,1,'2014-05-16 10:41:26','2014-05-16 10:41:26','As we have talked about before, when we first came to the idea it was focused on the opportunity that we uncovered for a unique ad delivery via mobile devices. We looked at the\r\n\r\nWhen we finally turned to try and find a name for our venture we struggled as nothing quite fit.\r\n\r\nWe\r\n\r\nThe name “Adora” came about during a conversation with my brother when we discussed the app idea and I asked him if he had any name suggestions. We started brainstorming and he began throwing out ideas, such as, “Ad-ittude” which is one of the names I remember he mentioned. From that thought I said “Ad-ora”, which was meant to be a spin-off of “Pandora” because our concept seemed to be like an “ad” version of Pandora, the automated music recommendation service. Our app will be an ad recommendation service with the single mission of delivering ads you’ll love (we may not want to present it as a knock off of pandora?…).\r\n\r\nLater we discovered that the name adora is a feminine name and actually means “gift”; “beloved”; “adored” and is of Greek, Old German, and Latin origin. The name is also associated with the root word to “love” which is “adorare” in Latin. For example, “adora” in Portuguese (a latin-based language) means “love.”\r\n\r\nThis meaning fits not only perfectly with the charity focus of the app, which can be described as providing “gifts” to charity motivated by “love”, but also the fact that our mission is to deliver only ads that you will “love” based on the app’s ability to learn over time from user activity which ads are relevant and desirable (we may not want to promise this yet?…)','The Story Behind a Name','','inherit','open','open','','381-revision-v1','','','2014-05-16 10:41:26','2014-05-16 10:41:26','',381,'http://getadora.com/381-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(385,1,'2014-05-16 11:03:43','2014-05-16 11:03:43','In the beginning we worked without a real name, just an acronym, so when we finally turned to try and find a name for our venture we struggled as nothing quite fit.\r\n\r\nIn late April we took the few ideas we did have and put them to our friends and family in the form of a survey but even then many stated that the right name did not seem to be on the list.\r\n\r\nThe name “Adora” came about during a conversation with my brother when we discussed the app idea and I asked him if he had any name suggestions. We started brainstorming and he began throwing out ideas, such as, “Ad-ittude” which is one of the names I remember he mentioned. From that thought I said “Ad-ora”, after saying it I immediately thought of “Pandora” and it made sense as our concept seemed to be like an “ad” version of Pandora, the automated music recommendation service. Our app will be an ad recommendation service with the single mission of delivering ads you’ll love. Rather than music in return we all get to do good.\r\n\r\nAs we\'ve done with every other name idea, we looked at it from all directions. I speak fluent Spanish so Latin based words feel at home with me, because of this I knew that Adora was a feminine name. This made sense as we all know the gentler sex is more giving, loving and full of charity.\r\n\r\nLater, as we researched the name, we found that adora means “gift”; “beloved”; “adored” and is of Greek, Old German, and Latin origin. The name is also associated with the root word to “love” which is “adorare” in Latin. For example, “adora” in Portuguese (a latin-based language) means “love.”\r\n\r\nThis meaning fits not only perfectly with the charity focus of the app, which can be described as providing “gifts” to charity motivated by “love”, but also the fact that our mission is to deliver only ads that you will “love” based on the app’s ability to learn over time from user activity which ads are relevant and desirable.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','The Story Behind a Name','','inherit','open','open','','381-revision-v1','','','2014-05-16 11:03:43','2014-05-16 11:03:43','',381,'http://getadora.com/381-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(386,1,'2014-05-16 11:10:00','2014-05-16 11:10:00','In the beginning we worked without a real name, just an acronym, so when we finally turned to try and find a name for our venture we struggled as nothing quite fit.\r\n\r\nIn late April we took the few ideas we did have and put them to our friends and family in the form of a survey but even then many stated that the right name did not seem to be on the list.\r\n\r\nThe name “Adora” came about during a conversation with my brother when we discussed the app idea and I asked him if he had any name suggestions. We started brainstorming and he began throwing out ideas, such as, “Ad-ittude” which is one of the names I remember he mentioned. From that thought I said “Ad-ora”, after saying it I immediately thought of “Pandora” and it made sense as our concept seemed to be like an “ad” version of Pandora, the automated music recommendation service. Our app will be an ad recommendation service with the single mission of delivering ads you’ll love. Rather than music in return we all get to do good.\r\n\r\nAs we\'ve done with every other name idea, we looked at it from all directions. I speak fluent Spanish so Latin based words feel at home with me, because of this I knew that Adora was a feminine name. This made sense as we all know the gentler sex is more giving, loving and full of charity.\r\n\r\nLater, as we researched the name, we found that adora means “gift”; “beloved”; “adored” and is of Greek, Old German, and Latin origin. The name is also associated with the root word to “love” which is “adorare” in Latin. For example, “adora” in Portuguese (a latin-based language) means “love.”\r\n\r\nThis meaning fits not only perfectly with the charity focus of the app, which can be described as providing “gifts” to charity motivated by “love”, but also the fact that our mission is to deliver only ads that you will “love” based on the app’s ability to learn over time from user activity which ads are relevant and desirable.\r\n\r\nThere is not much more to tell about the discovery of our name but as we have shared it with others everyone has fallen in love with both the name and the meaning. We invite you to do the same, join us in our passion to love our fellow man.','The Story Behind a Name','','inherit','open','open','','381-revision-v1','','','2014-05-16 11:10:00','2014-05-16 11:10:00','',381,'http://getadora.com/381-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(387,1,'2014-05-16 11:15:24','2014-05-16 11:15:24','For the past few months we\'ve been working on this idea, one that just might help a lot of people, but we didn\'t have a name.\r\n\r\nUntil today.\r\n\r\nWe are pleased to introduce you to <strong>Adora.</strong>\r\n\r\n<a title=\"The Story Behind a Name\" href=\"http://getadora.com/story-behind-name/\">Read more about how we came to be named so well.</a>','Welcome to Adora','','inherit','open','open','','377-revision-v1','','','2014-05-16 11:15:24','2014-05-16 11:15:24','',377,'http://getadora.com/377-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(388,1,'2014-05-16 11:24:41','2014-05-16 11:24:41','','WebLogoSeaGreenLg','','inherit','open','open','','weblogoseagreenlg','','','2014-05-16 11:24:41','2014-05-16 11:24:41','',381,'http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/WebLogoSeaGreenLg.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(389,4,'2014-04-30 12:30:28','2014-04-30 12:30:28','As we\'ve decided to introduce ourselves here is my story, how I came to be a founder of Adora.\r\n\r\nIn February of this year (2014) I went to a basketball game with Kyle. We were invited by Wayne, now our legal council, for a networking event sponsored by Ghost Armor. The event was in a catered private box for a Phoenix Suns game. I was there more for the fun than for business and I knew Kyle was there for much the same reason. Kyle owns and runs an all natural farm that focuses on Grass Fed Beef so networking in the business world can help but it was clear that the night was about having fun. With this being said Kyle hit it off with the head of sales for Ghost Armor, James, and being a former marketing consultant he couldn\'t help but ask about their marketing strategy. We enjoyed the game not knowing the seeds that had been planted.\r\n\r\nIt was through this conversation and a few others afterward that Kyle recognized the unique advertising opportunity that we now target.\r\n\r\nWhen he talked to me about it we both recognized the potential of the new advertising app right from the beginning. While I knew the success it could have, the excitement I felt was shallow. The was a significant piece of our business that was still missing: <strong>It had no heart.</strong>\r\n\r\nKyle quickly included Mark in our early discussions and the three of us quite a few meetings before it all started to fall together.\r\n\r\nWhen we stumbled upon adding the charity focus into our business plan, I knew we had found not just another piece but the heart of the business. It started as a supporting activity of the business but as Kyle, Mark and I continued to talk about the idea we all lit up more and more at the thought of all the good that might be done.\r\n\r\nThe days after the idea came to us I couldn’t help but constantly think about all the good that could be done by partnering with charities and appealing to users. We soon admitted to ourselves that we could not avoid making the charitable focus our main focus, not with all the good that could be done. We knew that if this business took off, as we hoped it would, that our families would be taken care of and that beyond that we would feel ungrateful and even embarrassed to not give all we could.\r\n\r\nThe problem with our idea is the difficulty in finding investors who will support our goal of giving away more profits than we keep BUT we have been blessed to have found encouragement and support at every turn.\r\n\r\nSo now I know that every hour I work, every idea, every improvement, every solution will translate into donations going directly to charities. A pursuit worthy of all the time, energy, and talent that I possessed.\r\n\r\nOur motto is simple: <strong>Do as much much good as we can - </strong>This is something I can stand for!\r\n\r\nBen Fa\'anunu','Passion - Ben Fa\'anunu','','publish','open','open','','passion-ben-faanunu','','','2014-05-20 21:37:53','2014-05-20 21:37:53','',0,'http://getadora.com/?p=389',0,'post','',0),(390,1,'2014-05-16 12:04:18','2014-05-16 12:04:18','As we\'ve decided to introduce ourselves here is my story, how I came to be a founder of Adora.\r\n\r\nWe recognized the potential of the new advertising app as soon as we began discussing it. While I knew the success it could have, the excitement I felt was shallow. The was a significant piece of our business that was still missing: It had no heart.\r\n\r\nWhen we introduced the charity aspect into our business plan, I knew we had found the heart of the business. I couldn’t help but think about all the good that could be done by partnering with charities and appealing to users. I know that with every idea, every improvement, every solution will translate into donations going directly to charities. A pursuit worthy of all the time, energy, and talent that I possessed.\r\n\r\nOur motto is simple: Do as much much good as we can.','Passion - Ben Fa\'anunu','','inherit','open','open','','389-revision-v1','','','2014-05-16 12:04:18','2014-05-16 12:04:18','',389,'http://getadora.com/389-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(391,1,'2014-05-16 12:30:28','2014-05-16 12:30:28','As we\'ve decided to introduce ourselves here is my story, how I came to be a founder of Adora.\r\n\r\nIn February of this year (2014) I went to a basketball game with Kyle. We were invited by Wayne, now our legal council, for a networking event sponsored by Ghost Armor. The event was in a catered private box for a Phoenix Suns game. I was there more for the fun than for business and I knew Kyle was there for much the same reason. Kyle owns and runs an all natural farm that focuses on Grass Fed Beef so networking in the business world can help but it was clear that the night was about having fun. With this being said Kyle hit it off with the head of sales for Ghost Armor, James, and being a former marketing consultant he couldn\'t help but ask about their marketing strategy. We enjoyed the game not knowing the seeds that had been planted.\r\n\r\nIt was through this conversation and a few others afterward that Kyle recognized the unique advertising opportunity that we now target.\r\n\r\nWhen he talked to me about it we both recognized the potential of the new advertising app right from the beginning. While I knew the success it could have, the excitement I felt was shallow. The was a significant piece of our business that was still missing: <strong>It had no heart.</strong>\r\n\r\nKyle quickly included Mark in our early discussions and the three of us quite a few meetings before it all started to fall together.\r\n\r\nWhen we stumbled upon adding the charity focus into our business plan, I knew we had found not just another piece but the heart of the business. It started as a supporting activity of the business but as Kyle, Mark and I continued to talk about the idea we all lit up more and more at the thought of all the good we might be done.\r\n\r\nThe days after the idea came to us I couldn’t help but constantly think about all the good that could be done by partnering with charities and appealing to users. We soon admitted to ourselves that we could not avoid making the charitable focus our main focus, not with all the good that could be done. We knew that if this business took off, as we hoped it would, that our families would be taken care of and that beyond that we would feel ungrateful and even embarrassed to not give all we could.\r\n\r\nThe problem with our idea is the difficulty in finding investors who will support our goal of giving away more profits than we keep BUT we have been blessed to have found encouragement and support at every turn.\r\n\r\nSo now I know that every hour I work, every idea, every improvement, every solution will translate into donations going directly to charities. A pursuit worthy of all the time, energy, and talent that I possessed.\r\n\r\nOur motto is simple: <strong>Do as much much good as we can - </strong>This is something I can stand for!\r\n\r\nBen Fa\'anunu','Passion - Ben Fa\'anunu','','inherit','open','open','','389-revision-v1','','','2014-05-16 12:30:28','2014-05-16 12:30:28','',389,'http://getadora.com/389-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(392,3,'2014-05-02 12:38:56','2014-05-02 12:38:56','\"The Charitable Corporation\" from a Drucker Perspective\r\n\r\nIt could take a considerable amount of time to write an article that would do justice to a distinguished figurehead, such as Peter Drucker, but I would like to talk about how his life contributions and how a large part of his career focused on the non-profit sector and how he believed that the social and private sectors could and do benefit each other.\r\n\r\nIn this context, I present the following questions: Can management planning be based on its mission to do good and on generating financial returns simultaneously? Is the term \"Charitable Corporation\" an oxymoron?\r\n\r\nThough I attended the Drucker School of Management, which is named after the man Peter Drucker himself \"the Father of Modern Management\", in Claremont, California for MBA school from 2010 - 2013, my time there only began to skim the surface of what will be a lifetime study of Drucker\'s ideas and teachings. Peter Drucker began teaching at the school in 1971 when he started the executive MBA program. The school was named in his honor in 1987. He taught his last class in 2002, thus completing more than 30 years as a professor at the school. He died in 2005.\r\n\r\nDrucker was born at the turn of the 20th Century in Vienna in 1909 prior to the start of World War 1. He had direct exposure as a child to some of the greatest minds, scientists, and philosophers such as Sigmund Freud and Joseph Schumpeter who attended gatherings in his home organized by his father to discuss new ideas and events.\r\n\r\nHis professional career spanned over 70 years and he wrote 39 books and numberless articles. During his career he advised the leaders of companies such as GE, IBM, Proctor &amp; Gamble and essentially composed \"the bible\" on management. He was a \"social ecologist\" and \"business philosopher.\" His ideas not only revolutionized corporate America as we know it today, but he invented corporate management. Prominent among his teachings is the principle that management is a \"liberal art\" that extends across many disciplines, such as art, literature, history, philosophy, humanities, etc. Drucker said the following about management as a liberal art:\r\n\r\n“Management deals with action and application; and its test is its results. This makes it a technology…But management also deals with people, their values, their growth and development— and this makes it a humanity…Management is thus what tradition used to call a ‘liberal art’.\" (see Peter F. Drucker, The New Realities, Page 223)\r\n\r\nTraditionally nonprofit organizations or what Drucker called the \"social sector\" have been severely lacking in management capabilities both in managing finances and managing employees. Drucker believed the social sector was necessary, however, for a healthy society because it fosters strong communities that work together and gives greater purpose to life. A substantial part of his career focused on the social sector. He advised organizations such as pastoral churches, the Salvation Army, the Red Cross, the Girl Scouts.\r\n\r\nDrucker taught that there is not an inherent contradiction between good business and the task of bettering society. In fact, Drucker advocated strongly for corporate social responsibility, which entails the duty to “do no harm” but also to solve societal ills.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately we have learned from history that when societal problems are left to government to solve, it is not done effectively. Drucker said that social problems can be turned into economic opportunities (see Peter F. Drucker, “The New Meaning of Corporate Social Responsibility.”California Management Review, 1984, 26: 53-63).\r\n\r\nToday, we can observe that more and more companies are finding that a business case can be made for corporate social responsibility and that this can actually increase profitability, especially when a company\'s philanthropic activities are aligned with its core competencies (see https://blogs.law.harvard.edu/corpgov/2011/06/26/the-business-case-for-corporate-social-responsibility/). For instance, an example cited in the article just referenced is how \"Home Depot Inc. provided rebuilding knowhow to the communities victimized by Hurricane Katrina.\"\r\n\r\nDrucker said, “Business enterprises are . . . organs of society. They do not exist for their own sake, but to fulfill a specific social purpose.” “Free enterprise cannot be justified as being good for business; it can be justified only as being good for society.” (see –Peter Drucker, Management: Tasks, Responsibilities, Practices).\r\n\r\nI return to the question presented at the outset, Do for-profit corporations and nonprofit organizations have to be mutually exclusive? Can a corporation have a mission to do good and still compete successfully in the private sector and generate profits and not rely on donations? Enter Adora, a new breed of corporation, the charitable corporation. Can it bridge the divide? Only time will tell.\r\n\r\nLeave your thoughts on these questions in the comments below.\r\n\r\nCheck out Jim Collins\' 2 minute tribute to Drucker here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wwpKN1hmMzQ\r\n\r\nHere is a link to the Drucker Institute that contains a vast amount of information and links to Drucker and his works: http://www.druckerinstitute.com/\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','The Charitable Corporation','','publish','open','open','','charitable-corporation','','','2014-05-16 12:40:37','2014-05-16 12:40:37','',0,'http://getadora.com/?p=392',0,'post','',0),(393,1,'2014-05-16 12:35:40','2014-05-16 12:35:40','\"The Charitable Corporation\" from a Drucker Perspective\r\n\r\nIt could take a considerable amount of time to write an article that would do justice to a distinguished figurehead, such as Peter Drucker, but I would like to talk about how his life contributions and how a large part of his career focused on the non-profit sector and how he believed that the social and private sectors could and do benefit each other.\r\n\r\nIn this context, I present the following questions: Can management planning be based on its mission to do good and on generating financial returns simultaneously? Is the term \"Charitable Corporation\" an oxymoron?\r\n\r\nThough I attended the Drucker School of Management, which is named after the man Peter Drucker himself \"the Father of Modern Management\", in Claremont, California for MBA school from 2010 - 2013, my time there only began to skim the surface of what will be a lifetime study of Drucker\'s ideas and teachings. Peter Drucker began teaching at the school in 1971 when he started the executive MBA program. The school was named in his honor in 1987. He taught his last class in 2002, thus completing more than 30 years as a professor at the school. He died in 2005.\r\n\r\nDrucker was born at the turn of the 20th Century in Vienna in 1909 prior to the start of World War 1. He had direct exposure as a child to some of the greatest minds, scientists, and philosophers such as Sigmund Freud and Joseph Schumpeter who attended gatherings in his home organized by his father to discuss new ideas and events.\r\n\r\nHis professional career spanned over 70 years and he wrote 39 books and numberless articles. During his career he advised the leaders of companies such as GE, IBM, Proctor &amp; Gamble and essentially composed \"the bible\" on management. He was a \"social ecologist\" and \"business philosopher.\" His ideas not only revolutionized corporate America as we know it today, but he invented corporate management. Prominent among his teachings is the principle that management is a \"liberal art\" that extends across many disciplines, such as art, literature, history, philosophy, humanities, etc. Drucker said the following about management as a liberal art:\r\n\r\n“Management deals with action and application; and its test is its results. This makes it a technology…But management also deals with people, their values, their growth and development— and this makes it a humanity…Management is thus what tradition used to call a ‘liberal art’.\" (see Peter F. Drucker, The New Realities, Page 223)\r\n\r\nTraditionally nonprofit organizations or what Drucker called the \"social sector\" have been severely lacking in management capabilities both in managing finances and managing employees. Drucker believed the social sector was necessary, however, for a healthy society because it fosters strong communities that work together and gives greater purpose to life. A substantial part of his career focused on the social sector. He advised organizations such as pastoral churches, the Salvation Army, the Red Cross, the Girl Scouts.\r\n\r\nDrucker taught that there is not an inherent contradiction between good business and the task of bettering society. In fact, Drucker advocated strongly for corporate social responsibility, which entails the duty to “do no harm” but also to solve societal ills.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately we have learned from history that when societal problems are left to government to solve, it is not done effectively. Drucker said that social problems can be turned into economic opportunities (see Peter F. Drucker, “The New Meaning of Corporate Social Responsibility.”California Management Review, 1984, 26: 53-63).\r\n\r\nToday, we can observe that more and more companies are finding that a business case can be made for corporate social responsibility and that this can actually increase profitability, especially when a company\'s philanthropic activities are aligned with its core competencies (see https://blogs.law.harvard.edu/corpgov/2011/06/26/the-business-case-for-corporate-social-responsibility/). For instance, an example cited in the article just referenced is how \"Home Depot Inc. provided rebuilding knowhow to the communities victimized by Hurricane Katrina.\"\r\n\r\nDrucker said, “Business enterprises are . . . organs of society. They do not exist for their own sake, but to fulfill a specific social purpose.” “Free enterprise cannot be justified as being good for business; it can be justified only as being good for society.” (see –Peter Drucker, Management: Tasks, Responsibilities, Practices).\r\n\r\nI return to the question presented at the outset, Do for-profit corporations and nonprofit organizations have to be mutually exclusive? Can a corporation have a mission to do good and still compete successfully in the private sector and generate profits and not rely on donations? Enter Adora, a new breed of corporation, the charitable corporation. Can it bridge the divide? Only time will tell.\r\n\r\nLeave your thoughts on these questions in the comments below.\r\n\r\nCheck out Jim Collins\' 2 minute tribute to Drucker here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wwpKN1hmMzQ\r\n\r\nHere is a link to the Drucker Institute that contains a vast amount of information and links to Drucker and his works: http://www.druckerinstitute.com/\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','','','inherit','open','open','','392-revision-v1','','','2014-05-16 12:35:40','2014-05-16 12:35:40','',392,'http://getadora.com/392-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(394,1,'2014-05-16 12:36:01','2014-05-16 12:36:01','\"The Charitable Corporation\" from a Drucker Perspective\r\n\r\nIt could take a considerable amount of time to write an article that would do justice to a distinguished figurehead, such as Peter Drucker, but I would like to talk about how his life contributions and how a large part of his career focused on the non-profit sector and how he believed that the social and private sectors could and do benefit each other.\r\n\r\nIn this context, I present the following questions: Can management planning be based on its mission to do good and on generating financial returns simultaneously? Is the term \"Charitable Corporation\" an oxymoron?\r\n\r\nThough I attended the Drucker School of Management, which is named after the man Peter Drucker himself \"the Father of Modern Management\", in Claremont, Calif