, for a healthy society because it fosters strong communities that work together and gives greater purpose to life. A substantial part of his career focused on the social sector. He advised organizations such as pastoral churches, the Salvation Army, the Red Cross, the Girl Scouts.\r\n\r\nDrucker taught that there is not an inherent contradiction between good business and the task of bettering society. In fact, Drucker advocated strongly for corporate social responsibility, which entails the duty to “do no harm” but also to solve societal ills.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately we have learned from history that when societal problems are left to government to solve, it is not done effectively. Drucker said that social problems can be turned into economic opportunities (see Peter F. Drucker, “The New Meaning of Corporate Social Responsibility.”California Management Review, 1984, 26: 53-63).\r\n\r\nToday, we can observe that more and more companies are finding that a business case can be made for corporate social responsibility and that this can actually increase profitability, especially when a company\'s philanthropic activities are aligned with its core competencies (see https://blogs.law.harvard.edu/corpgov/2011/06/26/the-business-case-for-corporate-social-responsibility/). For instance, an example cited in the article just referenced is how \"Home Depot Inc. provided rebuilding knowhow to the communities victimized by Hurricane Katrina.\"\r\n\r\nDrucker said, “Business enterprises are . . . organs of society. They do not exist for their own sake, but to fulfill a specific social purpose.” “Free enterprise cannot be justified as being good for business; it can be justified only as being good for society.” (see –Peter Drucker, Management: Tasks, Responsibilities, Practices).\r\n\r\nI return to the question presented at the outset, Do for-profit corporations and nonprofit organizations have to be mutually exclusive? Can a corporation have a mission to do good and still compete successfully in the private sector and generate profits and not rely on donations? Enter Adora, a new breed of corporation, the charitable corporation. Can it bridge the divide? Only time will tell.\r\n\r\nLeave your thoughts on these questions in the comments below.\r\n\r\nCheck out Jim Collins\' 2 minute tribute to Drucker here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wwpKN1hmMzQ\r\n\r\nHere is a link to the Drucker Institute that contains a vast amount of information and links to Drucker and his works: http://www.druckerinstitute.com/\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','The Charitable Corporation','','inherit','open','open','','392-revision-v1','','','2014-05-16 12:36:01','2014-05-16 12:36:01','',392,'http://getadora.com/392-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(395,1,'2014-05-16 12:38:18','2014-05-16 12:38:18','','DruckerQuote','','inherit','open','open','','druckerquote','','','2014-05-16 12:38:18','2014-05-16 12:38:18','',392,'http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/DruckerQuote.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(397,5,'2014-02-18 14:17:32','2014-02-18 14:17:32','<pre><em>This post is backdated to show some history of our journey, it is a composite of my thoughts and feelings as this venture has progressed.\r\n\r\n</em>My name is Kyle Thomas and this is my account of the beginning of Adora.</pre>\r\nMy journey to the beginning of Adora started long before the inspiration for the app.\r\n\r\nIt started when I was a child.\r\n\r\nI do not come from wealth by our standards but after what I have seen in my few travels I now look back with gratitude for what I did have. What struck me as a child, and has since stayed with me all my life, is that we really are responsible for helping those around us.\r\n\r\nMy father and I have a very interesting relationship, as most of us do with our parents, but one thing I can look back on and be grateful for is the example he set for me when it came to helping others.\r\n\r\nHe helped when ever he could and did more for people that he did not know than any other man I have ever knows of his means. He taught me that actions are more valuable than money given. That giving fish is not the same thing as teaching the skill of fishing.\r\n\r\nThis has been a guiding principle for me my entire life. I cannot pass someone on the side of the road without thought of stopping, and while I often do stop I could listen to that voice pulling at me more often. When I see signs held by homeless I sometimes give money but often I\'ll share a meal, a conversation, and try to lift spirits.\r\n\r\nI will be the first to admit that I do not do enough and this is one of the reasons I am out of my mind excited, blessed and overjoyed at the opportunity that is before us with Adora. I do not deserve to be the standard bearer for this, I can think of many men and women right now who would be more deserving of this opportunity.\r\n\r\nI cannot, however, speak to any of these people being able to outwork me, out sweat me, or carry this message forward with more passion. If that is all I can do, work as hard as I can, yell as loud as I can, then I might be able to do some good.\r\n\r\n<strong>The Actual Idea</strong>\r\n\r\nI was invited to go to a professional basketball game by Wayne, one of our legal gurus on the team (Mark has a JD/MBA so we are blessed with two). I was able to bring a plus 1 so I asked Ben if he wanted to come. The game was really a networking event sponsored by Ghost Armor in their private, catered, box. While at this game I found myself unable to resist talking to our host, James, about their marketing strategy. I had seen a great deal of advertising in the stadium and I was wondering how they were measuring that impact. We talked, and as a former marketing consultant who really does enjoy the art of marketing, I was intrigued by the position Ghost Armor had in the market.\r\n\r\nWe kept it somewhat light at the game and made an appointment to talk again later. At one of these later appointments the idea for Adora hit me really out of the blue. I can take very little credit as I do believe in divine inspiration.\r\n\r\nIt became clear to me that there was an amazing opportunity for advertising that was not being taken advantage of when it came to mobile technology.\r\n\r\nWe are keeping that little tid bit secret for now as we don\'t want to give away a competitive advantage before we need to, but suffice it to say that it is a big enough idea that we might, if we pull it off, be able to create a better advertising opportunity than any other out there today. Bigger than Google is on mobile, bigger than Facebook or Twitter.\r\n\r\nThis is exciting enough as it is but there was something missing. Ben was the first person I really talked to about the opportunity. We knew we had a great idea but again Ben too felt like there was something more to the opportunity.  We brought Mark in and through our conversations we turned to corporate culture and then it hit us. We wanted to make volunteer work and charitable donations part of the very fabric of our company but it quickly became more than just a part.\r\n\r\nI\'m not sure if any one of us really came up with the idea to focus on charity. It just evolved. The more we talked about it the more we were brought back to the idea of giving to charity and doing good. It was the one part of the entire idea that excited us to a degree that we could not help but focus more and more on it. Finally we just stopped fighting it and decided to make it THE FOCUS.\r\n\r\nWe knew that for us to take real pride and pleasure in the creation of this business that our hard work, long hours, and sacrifice would have to be for something more than just money. See I own and run an all natural farm and business now and it is very fulfilling for me. I love that I have gone back to my roots. It is growing but when I look at the good my food can do compared to the good Adora can do I have been forced to place the farm on the back burner. This was not an easy choice but I am blessed with an amazing rancher for a partner and he is and will pick up the slack.\r\n\r\nknowing what good we can do is enough of a motivation that I am writing this after almost two weeks of 18 hour days. I am still jazzed, a little tired (it is 7:11 am and I\'ve been working all night) but so excited. How can I rest when there is an idea that could help thousands if not millions right in front of me?\r\n\r\nSo I will rest when and where I can, and I will work harder than I have ever in my life. And when the money comes in it will only serve to multiply my efforts. Money is not the goal, it is the tool, the method of doing good and until there are no hungry mouths, or cold feet, or diminished spirits or, or , or... I will not relax my efforts. This is my commitment, my desire, and I will find joy and fulfillment in it.\r\n\r\nMy name is Kyle Thomas, and I am but a servant to a much greater cause. Join me, help me, work with me, and together we can do good things.','The Inspiration - Kyle Thomas','','publish','open','open','','inspiration-kyle-thomas','','','2014-05-22 02:39:42','2014-05-22 02:39:42','',0,'http://getadora.com/?p=397',0,'post','',0),(398,1,'2014-05-16 14:17:32','2014-05-16 14:17:32','<pre><em>This post is backdated to show some history of our journey, it is a composite of my thoughts and feelings as this venture has progressed.\r\n\r\n</em>My name is Kyle Thomas and this is my account of the beginning of Adora.</pre>\r\nMy journey to the beginning of Adora started long before the inspiration for the app.\r\n\r\nIt started when I was a child.\r\n\r\nI do not come from wealth by our standards but after what I have seen in my few travels I now look back with gratitude for what I did have. What struck me as a child, and has since stayed with me all my life, is that we really are responsible for helping those around us.\r\n\r\nMy father and I have a very interesting relationship, as most of us do with our parents, but one thing I can look back on and be grateful for is the example he set for me when it came to helping others.\r\n\r\nHe helped when ever he could and did more for people that he did not know than any other man I have ever knows of his means. He taught me that actions are more valuable than money given. That giving fish is not the same thing as teaching the skill of fishing.\r\n\r\nThis has been a guiding principle for me my entire life. I cannot pass someone on the side of the road without thought of stopping, and while I often do stop I could listen to that voice pulling at me more often. When I see signs held by homeless I sometimes give money but often I\'ll share a meal and talk and try to lift spirits.\r\n\r\nI will be the first to admit that I do not do enough and this is one of the reasons I am out of my mind excited, blessed and overjoyed at the opportunity that is before us with Adora. I do not deserve to be the standard bearer for this, I can think of many men and women right now who would be more deserving of this opportunity.\r\n\r\nI cannot, however, speak to any of these people being able to outwork me, out sweat me, or carry this message forward with more passion. If that is all I can do, work as hard as I can, then I might be able to do some good.\r\n\r\n<strong>The Actual Idea</strong>\r\n\r\nI was invited to go to a professional basketball game by Wayne, one of our legal gurus on the team (Mark has a JD/MBA so we are blessed with two). I was able to bring a plus 1 so I asked Ben if he wanted to come. The game was really a networking event sponsored by Ghost Armor in their private, catered, box. While at this game I found myself unable to resist talking to our host, James, about their marketing strategy. I had seen a great deal of advertising in the stadium and I was wondering how they were measuring that impact. We talked and as a former marketing consultant who really does enjoy the art of marketing I was intrigued by the position Ghost Armor had in the market.\r\n\r\nWe kept it somewhat light at the game and made an appointment to talk again later. At one of these later appointments the idea for Adora hit me really out of the blue. I can take very little credit as I do believe in divine inspiration.\r\n\r\nIt became clear to me that there was an amazing opportunity for advertising that was not being taken advantage of when it came to mobile technology.\r\n\r\nWe are keeping that little tid bit secret for now as we don\'t want to give away a competitive advantage before we need to, but suffice it to say that it is a big enough idea that we might, if we pull it off, be able to create a better advertising opportunity than any other out there today. Bigger than Google is on mobile, bigger than Facebook or Twitter.\r\n\r\nThis is exciting enough as it is but there was something missing. Ben was the first person I really talked to about the opportunity outside of my sweet wife. We knew we had a great idea but again Ben too felt like there was something more to the opportunity.  We brought Mark in and through our conversations we turned to corporate culture and then it hit us.\r\n\r\nI\'m not sure if any one of us really came up with the idea to focus on charity. It just evolved. The more we talked about it the more we were brought back to the idea of giving to charity and doing good. It was the one part of the entire idea that excited us to a degree that we could not help but focus more and more on it. Finally we just stopped fighting it and decided to make it THE FOCUS.\r\n\r\nWe knew that for us to take real pride and pleasure in the creation of this business that our hard work, long hours, and sacrifice would have to be for something more than just money. See I own and run an all natural farm and business now and it is very fulfilling for me. I love that i have gone back to my roots. It is growing but when I look at the good my food can do compared to the good Adora can do I have been forced to place the farm on the back burner. This was not an easy choice but I am blessed with an amazing rancher for a partner and he is and will pick up the slack.\r\n\r\nknowing what good we can do is enough of a motivation that I am writing this after almost two weeks of 18 hour days. I am still jazzed, a little tired (it is 7:11 am and I\'ve been working all night) but so excited. How can I rest when there is an idea that could help thousands if not millions right in front of me?\r\n\r\nSo I will rest when and where I can, and I will work harder than I have ever in my life. And when the money comes in it will only serve to multiply my efforts. Money is not the goal, it is the tool, the method of doing good and until there are no hungry mouths, or cold feet, or diminished spirits or, or , or... I will not relax my efforts. This is my commitment, my desire, and I will find joy and fulfillment in it.\r\n\r\nMy name is Kyle Thomas, and I am but a servant to a much greater cause. Join me, help me, work with me, and together we can do good things.','The Inspiration - Kyle Thomas','','inherit','open','open','','397-revision-v1','','','2014-05-16 14:17:32','2014-05-16 14:17:32','',397,'http://getadora.com/397-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(399,1,'2014-05-20 21:37:53','2014-05-20 21:37:53','As we\'ve decided to introduce ourselves here is my story, how I came to be a founder of Adora.\r\n\r\nIn February of this year (2014) I went to a basketball game with Kyle. We were invited by Wayne, now our legal council, for a networking event sponsored by Ghost Armor. The event was in a catered private box for a Phoenix Suns game. I was there more for the fun than for business and I knew Kyle was there for much the same reason. Kyle owns and runs an all natural farm that focuses on Grass Fed Beef so networking in the business world can help but it was clear that the night was about having fun. With this being said Kyle hit it off with the head of sales for Ghost Armor, James, and being a former marketing consultant he couldn\'t help but ask about their marketing strategy. We enjoyed the game not knowing the seeds that had been planted.\r\n\r\nIt was through this conversation and a few others afterward that Kyle recognized the unique advertising opportunity that we now target.\r\n\r\nWhen he talked to me about it we both recognized the potential of the new advertising app right from the beginning. While I knew the success it could have, the excitement I felt was shallow. The was a significant piece of our business that was still missing: <strong>It had no heart.</strong>\r\n\r\nKyle quickly included Mark in our early discussions and the three of us quite a few meetings before it all started to fall together.\r\n\r\nWhen we stumbled upon adding the charity focus into our business plan, I knew we had found not just another piece but the heart of the business. It started as a supporting activity of the business but as Kyle, Mark and I continued to talk about the idea we all lit up more and more at the thought of all the good that might be done.\r\n\r\nThe days after the idea came to us I couldn’t help but constantly think about all the good that could be done by partnering with charities and appealing to users. We soon admitted to ourselves that we could not avoid making the charitable focus our main focus, not with all the good that could be done. We knew that if this business took off, as we hoped it would, that our families would be taken care of and that beyond that we would feel ungrateful and even embarrassed to not give all we could.\r\n\r\nThe problem with our idea is the difficulty in finding investors who will support our goal of giving away more profits than we keep BUT we have been blessed to have found encouragement and support at every turn.\r\n\r\nSo now I know that every hour I work, every idea, every improvement, every solution will translate into donations going directly to charities. A pursuit worthy of all the time, energy, and talent that I possessed.\r\n\r\nOur motto is simple: <strong>Do as much much good as we can - </strong>This is something I can stand for!\r\n\r\nBen Fa\'anunu','Passion - Ben Fa\'anunu','','inherit','open','open','','389-revision-v1','','','2014-05-20 21:37:53','2014-05-20 21:37:53','',389,'http://getadora.com/389-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(400,1,'2014-05-20 21:40:35','2014-05-20 21:40:35','<pre><em>This post is backdated to show some history of our journey, it is a composite of my thoughts and feelings as this venture has progressed.\r\n\r\n</em>My name is Kyle Thomas and this is my account of the beginning of Adora.</pre>\r\nMy journey to the beginning of Adora started long before the inspiration for the app.\r\n\r\nIt started when I was a child.\r\n\r\nI do not come from wealth by our standards but after what I have seen in my few travels I now look back with gratitude for what I did have. What struck me as a child, and has since stayed with me all my life, is that we really are responsible for helping those around us.\r\n\r\nMy father and I have a very interesting relationship, as most of us do with our parents, but one thing I can look back on and be grateful for is the example he set for me when it came to helping others.\r\n\r\nHe helped when ever he could and did more for people that he did not know than any other man I have ever knows of his means. He taught me that actions are more valuable than money given. That giving fish is not the same thing as teaching the skill of fishing.\r\n\r\nThis has been a guiding principle for me my entire life. I cannot pass someone on the side of the road without thought of stopping, and while I often do stop I could listen to that voice pulling at me more often. When I see signs held by homeless I sometimes give money but often I\'ll share a meal, a conversation, and try to lift spirits.\r\n\r\nI will be the first to admit that I do not do enough and this is one of the reasons I am out of my mind excited, blessed and overjoyed at the opportunity that is before us with Adora. I do not deserve to be the standard bearer for this, I can think of many men and women right now who would be more deserving of this opportunity.\r\n\r\nI cannot, however, speak to any of these people being able to outwork me, out sweat me, or carry this message forward with more passion. If that is all I can do, work as hard as I can, then I might be able to do some good.\r\n\r\n<strong>The Actual Idea</strong>\r\n\r\nI was invited to go to a professional basketball game by Wayne, one of our legal gurus on the team (Mark has a JD/MBA so we are blessed with two). I was able to bring a plus 1 so I asked Ben if he wanted to come. The game was really a networking event sponsored by Ghost Armor in their private, catered, box. While at this game I found myself unable to resist talking to our host, James, about their marketing strategy. I had seen a great deal of advertising in the stadium and I was wondering how they were measuring that impact. We talked and as a former marketing consultant who really does enjoy the art of marketing I was intrigued by the position Ghost Armor had in the market.\r\n\r\nWe kept it somewhat light at the game and made an appointment to talk again later. At one of these later appointments the idea for Adora hit me really out of the blue. I can take very little credit as I do believe in divine inspiration.\r\n\r\nIt became clear to me that there was an amazing opportunity for advertising that was not being taken advantage of when it came to mobile technology.\r\n\r\nWe are keeping that little tid bit secret for now as we don\'t want to give away a competitive advantage before we need to, but suffice it to say that it is a big enough idea that we might, if we pull it off, be able to create a better advertising opportunity than any other out there today. Bigger than Google is on mobile, bigger than Facebook or Twitter.\r\n\r\nThis is exciting enough as it is but there was something missing. Ben was the first person I really talked to about the opportunity outside of my sweet wife. We knew we had a great idea but again Ben too felt like there was something more to the opportunity.  We brought Mark in and through our conversations we turned to corporate culture and then it hit us.\r\n\r\nI\'m not sure if any one of us really came up with the idea to focus on charity. It just evolved. The more we talked about it the more we were brought back to the idea of giving to charity and doing good. It was the one part of the entire idea that excited us to a degree that we could not help but focus more and more on it. Finally we just stopped fighting it and decided to make it THE FOCUS.\r\n\r\nWe knew that for us to take real pride and pleasure in the creation of this business that our hard work, long hours, and sacrifice would have to be for something more than just money. See I own and run an all natural farm and business now and it is very fulfilling for me. I love that i have gone back to my roots. It is growing but when I look at the good my food can do compared to the good Adora can do I have been forced to place the farm on the back burner. This was not an easy choice but I am blessed with an amazing rancher for a partner and he is and will pick up the slack.\r\n\r\nknowing what good we can do is enough of a motivation that I am writing this after almost two weeks of 18 hour days. I am still jazzed, a little tired (it is 7:11 am and I\'ve been working all night) but so excited. How can I rest when there is an idea that could help thousands if not millions right in front of me?\r\n\r\nSo I will rest when and where I can, and I will work harder than I have ever in my life. And when the money comes in it will only serve to multiply my efforts. Money is not the goal, it is the tool, the method of doing good and until there are no hungry mouths, or cold feet, or diminished spirits or, or , or... I will not relax my efforts. This is my commitment, my desire, and I will find joy and fulfillment in it.\r\n\r\nMy name is Kyle Thomas, and I am but a servant to a much greater cause. Join me, help me, work with me, and together we can do good things.','The Inspiration - Kyle Thomas','','inherit','open','open','','397-revision-v1','','','2014-05-20 21:40:35','2014-05-20 21:40:35','',397,'http://getadora.com/397-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(401,1,'2014-05-20 21:43:05','2014-05-20 21:43:05','<pre><em>This post is backdated to show some history of our journey, it is a composite of my thoughts and feelings as this venture has progressed.\n\n</em>My name is Kyle Thomas and this is my account of the beginning of Adora.</pre>\nMy journey to the beginning of Adora started long before the inspiration for the app.\n\nIt started when I was a child.\n\nI do not come from wealth by our standards but after what I have seen in my few travels I now look back with gratitude for what I did have. What struck me as a child, and has since stayed with me all my life, is that we really are responsible for helping those around us.\n\nMy father and I have a very interesting relationship, as most of us do with our parents, but one thing I can look back on and be grateful for is the example he set for me when it came to helping others.\n\nHe helped when ever he could and did more for people that he did not know than any other man I have ever knows of his means. He taught me that actions are more valuable than money given. That giving fish is not the same thing as teaching the skill of fishing.\n\nThis has been a guiding principle for me my entire life. I cannot pass someone on the side of the road without thought of stopping, and while I often do stop I could listen to that voice pulling at me more often. When I see signs held by homeless I sometimes give money but often I\'ll share a meal, a conversation, and try to lift spirits.\n\nI will be the first to admit that I do not do enough and this is one of the reasons I am out of my mind excited, blessed and overjoyed at the opportunity th