er than Facebook or Twitter.\r\n\r\nThis is exciting enough as it is but there was something missing. Ben was the first person I really talked to about the opportunity outside of my sweet wife. We knew we had a great idea but again Ben too felt like there was something more to the opportunity.  We brought Mark in and through our conversations we turned to corporate culture and then it hit us. We wanted to make volunteer work and charitable donations part of the very fabric of our company but it quickly became more than just a part.\r\n\r\nI\'m not sure if any one of us really came up with the idea to focus on charity. It just evolved. The more we talked about it the more we were brought back to the idea of giving to charity and doing good. It was the one part of the entire idea that excited us to a degree that we could not help but focus more and more on it. Finally we just stopped fighting it and decided to make it THE FOCUS.\r\n\r\nWe knew that for us to take real pride and pleasure in the creation of this business that our hard work, long hours, and sacrifice would have to be for something more than just money. See I own and run an all natural farm and business now and it is very fulfilling for me. I love that i have gone back to my roots. It is growing but when I look at the good my food can do compared to the good Adora can do I have been forced to place the farm on the back burner. This was not an easy choice but I am blessed with an amazing rancher for a partner and he is and will pick up the slack.\r\n\r\nknowing what good we can do is enough of a motivation that I am writing this after almost two weeks of 18 hour days. I am still jazzed, a little tired (it is 7:11 am and I\'ve been working all night) but so excited. How can I rest when there is an idea that could help thousands if not millions right in front of me?\r\n\r\nSo I will rest when and where I can, and I will work harder than I have ever in my life. And when the money comes in it will only serve to multiply my efforts. Money is not the goal, it is the tool, the method of doing good and until there are no hungry mouths, or cold feet, or diminished spirits or, or , or... I will not relax my efforts. This is my commitment, my desire, and I will find joy and fulfillment in it.\r\n\r\nMy name is Kyle Thomas, and I am but a servant to a much greater cause. Join me, help me, work with me, and together we can do good things.','The Inspiration - Kyle Thomas','','inherit','open','open','','397-revision-v1','','','2014-05-20 21:43:49','2014-05-20 21:43:49','',397,'http://getadora.com/397-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(404,1,'2014-05-20 21:44:33','2014-05-20 21:44:33','<pre><em>This post is backdated to show some history of our journey, it is a composite of my thoughts and feelings as this venture has progressed.\r\n\r\n</em>My name is Kyle Thomas and this is my account of the beginning of Adora.</pre>\r\nMy journey to the beginning of Adora started long before the inspiration for the app.\r\n\r\nIt started when I was a child.\r\n\r\nI do not come from wealth by our standards but after what I have seen in my few travels I now look back with gratitude for what I did have. What struck me as a child, and has since stayed with me all my life, is that we really are responsible for helping those around us.\r\n\r\nMy father and I have a very interesting relationship, as most of us do with our parents, but one thing I can look back on and be grateful for is the example he set for me when it came to helping others.\r\n\r\nHe helped when ever he could and did more for people that he did not know than any other man I have ever knows of his means. He taught me that actions are more valuable than money given. That giving fish is not the same thing as teaching the skill of fishing.\r\n\r\nThis has been a guiding principle for me my entire life. I cannot pass someone on the side of the road without thought of stopping, and while I often do stop I could listen to that voice pulling at me more often. When I see signs held by homeless I sometimes give money but often I\'ll share a meal, a conversation, and try to lift spirits.\r\n\r\nI will be the first to admit that I do not do enough and this is one of the reasons I am out of my mind excited, blessed and overjoyed at the opportunity that is before us with Adora. I do not deserve to be the standard bearer for this, I can think of many men and women right now who would be more deserving of this opportunity.\r\n\r\nI cannot, however, speak to any of these people being able to outwork me, out sweat me, or carry this message forward with more passion. If that is all I can do, work as hard as I can, yell as loud as I can, then I might be able to do some good.\r\n\r\n<strong>The Actual Idea</strong>\r\n\r\nI was invited to go to a professional basketball game by Wayne, one of our legal gurus on the team (Mark has a JD/MBA so we are blessed with two). I was able to bring a plus 1 so I asked Ben if he wanted to come. The game was really a networking event sponsored by Ghost Armor in their private, catered, box. While at this game I found myself unable to resist talking to our host, James, about their marketing strategy. I had seen a great deal of advertising in the stadium and I was wondering how they were measuring that impact. We talked, and as a former marketing consultant who really does enjoy the art of marketing, I was intrigued by the position Ghost Armor had in the market.\r\n\r\nWe kept it somewhat light at the game and made an appointment to talk again later. At one of these later appointments the idea for Adora hit me really out of the blue. I can take very little credit as I do believe in divine inspiration.\r\n\r\nIt became clear to me that there was an amazing opportunity for advertising that was not being taken advantage of when it came to mobile technology.\r\n\r\nWe are keeping that little tid bit secret for now as we don\'t want to give away a competitive advantage before we need to, but suffice it to say that it is a big enough idea that we might, if we pull it off, be able to create a better advertising opportunity than any other out there today. Bigger than Google is on mobile, bigger than Facebook or Twitter.\r\n\r\nThis is exciting enough as it is but there was something missing. Ben was the first person I really talked to about the opportunity outside of my sweet wife. We knew we had a great idea but again Ben too felt like there was something more to the opportunity.  We brought Mark in and through our conversations we turned to corporate culture and then it hit us. We wanted to make volunteer work and charitable donations part of the very fabric of our company but it quickly became more than just a part.\r\n\r\nI\'m not sure if any one of us really came up with the idea to focus on charity. It just evolved. The more we talked about it the more we were brought back to the idea of giving to charity and doing good. It was the one part of the entire idea that excited us to a degree that we could not help but focus more and more on it. Finally we just stopped fighting it and decided to make it THE FOCUS.\r\n\r\nWe knew that for us to take real pride and pleasure in the creation of this business that our hard work, long hours, and sacrifice would have to be for something more than just money. See I own and run an all natural farm and business now and it is very fulfilling for me. I love that I have gone back to my roots. It is growing but when I look at the good my food can do compared to the good Adora can do I have been forced to place the farm on the back burner. This was not an easy choice but I am blessed with an amazing rancher for a partner and he is and will pick up the slack.\r\n\r\nknowing what good we can do is enough of a motivation that I am writing this after almost two weeks of 18 hour days. I am still jazzed, a little tired (it is 7:11 am and I\'ve been working all night) but so excited. How can I rest when there is an idea that could help thousands if not millions right in front of me?\r\n\r\nSo I will rest when and where I can, and I will work harder than I have ever in my life. And when the money comes in it will only serve to multiply my efforts. Money is not the goal, it is the tool, the method of doing good and until there are no hungry mouths, or cold feet, or diminished spirits or, or , or... I will not relax my efforts. This is my commitment, my desire, and I will find joy and fulfillment in it.\r\n\r\nMy name is Kyle Thomas, and I am but a servant to a much greater cause. Join me, help me, work with me, and together we can do good things.','The Inspiration - Kyle Thomas','','inherit','open','open','','397-revision-v1','','','2014-05-20 21:44:33','2014-05-20 21:44:33','',397,'http://getadora.com/397-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(405,1,'2014-05-22 02:37:09','2014-05-22 02:37:09','Are you doing all you can for your fellow man?\r\n\r\nI know I can not say that I am.\r\n\r\nWhen I think about it I am ashamed. That I have a roof over my head when so many do not. That I have food when so many cannot say the same.\r\n\r\nI am embarrassed...\r\n\r\nI can do more.\r\n\r\nWe can do more.\r\n\r\nOver the next couple of months we are going to be posting simple, easy things you can do to make a difference.\r\n\r\nPlaces you can go and people who can direct you to places where your limited time can make the most impact.\r\n\r\nWe will be posting images and video of our efforts and we would love for you to do the same. We need to set examples and bring the needs of our fellow man to the for front of our minds.\r\n\r\njoin our mailing list to get these updates.','We can do more','','inherit','open','open','','353-revision-v1','','','2014-05-22 02:37:09','2014-05-22 02:37:09','',353,'http://getadora.com/353-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(406,1,'2014-05-22 02:38:52','2014-05-22 02:38:52','<pre><em>This post is backdated to show some history of our journey, it is a composite of my thoughts and feelings as this venture has progressed.\r\n\r\n</em>My name is Kyle Thomas and this is my account of the beginning of Adora.</pre>\r\nMy journey to the beginning of Adora started long before the inspiration for the app.\r\n\r\nIt started when I was a child.\r\n\r\nI do not come from wealth by our standards but after what I have seen in my few travels I now look back with gratitude for what I did have. What struck me as a child, and has since stayed with me all my life, is that we really are responsible for helping those around us.\r\n\r\nMy father and I have a very interesting relationship, as most of us do with our parents, but one thing I can look back on and be grateful for is the example he set for me when it came to helping others.\r\n\r\nHe helped when ever he could and did more for people that he did not know than any other man I have ever knows of his means. He taught me that actions are more valuable than money given. That giving fish is not the same thing as teaching the skill of fishing.\r\n\r\nThis has been a guiding principle for me my entire life. I cannot pass someone on the side of the road without thought of stopping, and while I often do stop I could listen to that voice pulling at me more often. When I see signs held by homeless I sometimes give money but often I\'ll share a meal, a conversation, and try to lift spirits.\r\n\r\nI will be the first to admit that I do not do enough and this is one of the reasons I am out of my mind excited, blessed and overjoyed at the opportunity that is before us with Adora. I do not deserve to be the standard bearer for this, I can think of many men and women right now who would be more deserving of this opportunity.\r\n\r\nI cannot, however, speak to any of these people being able to outwork me, out sweat me, or carry this message forward with more passion. If that is all I can do, work as hard as I can, yell as loud as I can, then I might be able to do some good.\r\n\r\n<strong>The Actual Idea</strong>\r\n\r\nI was invited to go to a professional basketball game by Wayne, one of our legal gurus on the team (Mark has a JD/MBA so we are blessed with two). I was able to bring a plus 1 so I asked Ben if he wanted to come. The game was really a networking event sponsored by Ghost Armor in their private, catered, box. While at this game I found myself unable to resist talking to our host, James, about their marketing strategy. I had seen a great deal of advertising in the stadium and I was wondering how they were measuring that impact. We talked, and as a former marketing consultant who really does enjoy the art of marketing, I was intrigued by the position Ghost Armor had in the market.\r\n\r\nWe kept it somewhat light at the game and made an appointment to talk again later. At one of these later appointments the idea for Adora hit me really out of the blue. I can take very little credit as I do believe in divine inspiration.\r\n\r\nIt became clear to me that there was an amazing opportunity for advertising that was not being taken advantage of when it came to mobile technology.\r\n\r\nWe are keeping that little tid bit secret for now as we don\'t want to give away a competitive advantage before we need to, but suffice it to say that it is a big enough idea that we might, if we pull it off, be able to create a better advertising opportunity than any other out there today. Bigger than Google is on mobile, bigger than Facebook or Twitter.\r\n\r\nThis is exciting enough as it is but there was something missing. Ben was the first person I really talked to about the opportunity. We knew we had a great idea but again Ben too felt like there was something more to the opportunity.  We brought Mark in and through our conversations we turned to corporate culture and then it hit us. We wanted to make volunteer work and charitable donations part of the very fabric of our company but it quickly became more than just a part.\r\n\r\nI\'m not sure if any one of us really came up with the idea to focus on charity. It just evolved. The more we talked about it the more we were brought back to the idea of giving to charity and doing good. It was the one part of the entire idea that excited us to a degree that we could not help but focus more and more on it. Finally we just stopped fighting it and decided to make it THE FOCUS.\r\n\r\nWe knew that for us to take real pride and pleasure in the creation of this business that our hard work, long hours, and sacrifice would have to be for something more than just money. See I own and run an all natural farm and business now and it is very fulfilling for me. I love that I have gone back to my roots. It is growing but when I look at the good my food can do compared to the good Adora can do I have been forced to place the farm on the back burner. This was not an easy choice but I am blessed with an amazing rancher for a partner and he is and will pick up the slack.\r\n\r\nknowing what good we can do is enough of a motivation that I am writing this after almost two weeks of 18 hour days. I am still jazzed, a little tired (it is 7:11 am and I\'ve been working all night) but so excited. How can I rest when there is an idea that could help thousands if not millions right in front of me?\r\n\r\nSo I will rest when and where I can, and I will work harder than I have ever in my life. And when the money comes in it will only serve to multiply my efforts. Money is not the goal, it is the tool, the method of doing good and until there are no hungry mouths, or cold feet, or diminished spirits or, or , or... I will not relax my efforts. This is my commitment, my desire, and I will find joy and fulfillment in it.\r\n\r\nMy name is Kyle Thomas, and I am but a servant to a much greater cause. Join me, help me, work with me, and together we can do good things.','The Inspiration - Kyle Thomas','','inherit','open','open','','397-revision-v1','','','2014-05-22 02:38:52','2014-05-22 02:38:52','',397,'http://getadora.com/397-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(408,1,'2014-05-22 12:44:28','2014-05-22 12:44:28','So I like to keep up with a lot of subjects and one of my favorite publications, online and in print is the Harvard Business Review.\r\n\r\nThis morning I came across and article by Clay Christensen and Derek van Bever titled - \"The Capitalists Dilemma\"\r\n\r\nGreat article and it sums up what is broken about Capitalism. Now on its face this actually contradicts the idea that <em>is</em> capitalism, the idea that it corrects itself so if it is broken it will just fix naturally.\r\n\r\nI agree with this to a point but I really like some of the points in the article:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','A plea for TALENT!','','inherit','open','open','','407-revision-v1','','','2014-05-22 12:44:28','2014-05-22 12:44:28','',407,'http://getadora.com/407-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(409,1,'2014-05-22 12:53:05','2014-05-22 12:53:05','So I like to keep up with a lot of subjects and one of my favorite publications, online and in print is the Harvard Business Review.\r\n\r\nThis morning I came across and article by Clay Christensen and Derek van Bever titled - \"<a title=\"The Capitalist’s Dilemma\" href=\"http://hbr.org/2014/06/the-capitalists-dilemma/ar/6\" target=\"_blank\">The Capitalists Dilemma</a>\"\r\n\r\nGreat article and it sums up what is broken about Capitalism. Now on its face this actually contradicts the idea that <em>is</em> capitalism, the idea that it corrects itself so if it is broken it will just fix naturally.\r\n\r\nI agree with this to a point but I really like some of the points in the article:\r\n\r\n1. The cash is there but the talent is not - we are having a hard time finding MEN and WOMEN who have the gumption to make hard choices. We see a lot of decision paralysis.\r\n\r\n2. Market-Creating Innovation is scary, capital intensive, risky and if it fails the financial markets punish you - see point 1.\r\n\r\n3. Long term, good decisions are discouraged because of investor pressure.\r\n\r\nThen at the end they talk about the shift in mindset that needs to be disseminated through business schools. Again we come back to talent.\r\n\r\nWe need to stop operating out of fear, and start making the right choices regardless of investor pressure. Like James &amp; Benton mention above, if we just act as we see we should the investors will either adjust or find other markets and businesses to invest in.\r\n\r\nI cant wait to see a market where the right choice is made regardless of stock reaction. Where we are brave enough to take that hit and move on because we KNOW it is the right long term choice.\r\n\r\nGreat article, thanks guys.','A plea for TALENT!','','inherit','open','open','','407-revision-v1','','','2014-05-22 12:53:05','2014-05-22 12:53:05','',407,'http://getadora.com/407-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(410,1,'2014-05-22 12:58:13','2014-05-22 12:58:13','','HBR','','inherit','open','open','','hbr','','','2014-05-22 12:58:13','2014-05-22 12:58:13','',407,'http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/HBR.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(411,1,'2014-05-22 13:16:13','2014-05-22 13:16:13','So I like to keep up with a lot of subjects and one of my favorite publications, online and in print is the Harvard Business Review.\n\nThis morning I came across and article by Clay Christensen and Derek van Bever titled - \"<a title=\"The Capitalist’s Dilemma\" href=\"http://hbr.org/2014/06/the-capitalists-dilemma/ar/6\" target=\"_blank\">The Capitalists Dilemma</a>\"\n\nGreat article and it sums up what is broken about Capitalism. Now on its face this actually contradicts the idea that <em>is</em> capitalism, the idea that it corrects itself so if it is broken it will just fix naturally.\n\nI agree with this to a point but I really like some of the points in the article:\n\n1. The cash is there but the talent is not - we are having a hard time finding MEN and WOMEN who have the gumption to make hard choices. We see a lot of decision paralysis.\n\n2. Market-Creating Innovation is scary, capital intensive, risky and if it fails the financial markets punish you - see point 1.\n\n3. Long term, good decisions are discouraged because of investor pressure.\n\nThen at the end they talk about the shift in mindset that needs to be disseminated through business schools. So again we come back to talent.\n\nWe need to stop operating out of fear, and start making the right choices regardless of investor pressure. Like James &amp; Benton mention above, if we just act as we see we should the investors will either adjust or find other markets and businesses to invest in.\n\nI cant wait to see a market where the right choice is made regardless of stock reaction. Where we are brave enough to take that hit and move on because we KNOW it is the right long term choice.\n\nWe are looking for talent right now, looking for people who don\'t need to be hand held. We want people who will fight for a decision they think is the right one, even if it might not be liked by our investors.\n\nDon\'t get me wrong, I love and will love our investors! BUT if they trust us enough to invest then I hope they trust us enough to stand next to us when we make the hard choices, because we will.','A plea for TALENT!','','inherit','open','open','','407-autosave-v1','','','2014-05-22 13:16:13','2014-05-22 13:16:13','',407,'http://getadora.com/407-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(412,1,'2014-05-22 13:16:16','2014-05-22 13:16:16','So I like to keep up with a lot of subjects and one of my favorite publications, online and in print is the Harvard Business Review.\r\n\r\nThis morning I came across and article by Clay Christensen and Derek van Bever titled - \"<a title=\"The Capitalist’s Dilemma\" href=\"http://hbr.org/2014/06/the-capitalists-dilemma/ar/6\" target=\"_blank\">The Capitalists Dilemma</a>\"\r\n\r\nGreat article and it sums up what is broken about Capitalism. Now on its face this actually contradicts the idea that <em>is</em> capitalism, the idea that it corrects itself so if it is broken it will just fix naturally.\r\n\r\nI agree with this to a point but I really like some of the points in the article:\r\n\r\n1. The cash is there but the talent is not - we are having a hard time finding MEN and WOMEN who have the gumption to make hard choices. We see a lot of decision paralysis.\r\n\r\n2. Market-Creating Innovation is scary, capital intensive, risky and if it fails the financial markets punish you - see point 1.\r\n\r\n3. Long term, good decisions are discouraged because of investor pressure.\r\n\r\nThen at the end they talk about the shift in mindset that needs to be disseminated through business schools. So again we come back to talent.\r\n\r\nWe need to stop operating out of fear, and start making the right choices regardless of investor pressure. Like James &amp; Benton mention above, if we just act as we see we should the investors will either adjust or find other markets and businesses to invest in.\r\n\r\nI cant wait to see a market where the right choice is made regardless of stock reaction. Where we are brave enough to take that hit and move on because we KNOW it is the right long term choice.\r\n\r\nWe are looking for talent right now, looking for people who don\'t need to be hand held. We want people who will fight for a decision they think is the right one, even if it might not be liked by our investors.\r\n\r\nDon\'t get me wrong, I love and will love our investors! BUT if they trust us enough to invest then I hope they trust us enough to stand next to us when we make the hard choices, because we will.','A plea for TALENT!','','inherit','open','open','','407-revision-v1','','','2014-05-22 13:16:16','2014-05-22 13:16:16','',407,'http://getadora.com/407-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(466,3,'2014-10-08 02:08:03','2014-10-08 02:08:03','<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Our passion at Adora is to do as much good as we possibly can.</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">This is what drives our every action and what makes our hearts burn to work harder, longer, and smarter.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Adora will ignite this passion in others to start a movement that is contagious, which will lead to a change in not just corporate giving but also in private giving too. Adora stands for the principle that even a dollar here or $5 there can make a difference--that you don\'t have to be wealthy to give and you don\'t have to give money to make an impact.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/RXMnDG3QzxE\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Read more <a title=\"Charity+\" href=\"http://getadora.com/about/charity/\">about Adora</a> or find out more <a title=\"The app\" href=\"http://getadora.com/about/adora-app/\">about the Adora app</a></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>If you would like to talk more or for additional info please feel free to <a title=\"Contact Us\" href=\"http://getadora.com/contact-us/\">contact us</a>.</strong></p>','About','','inherit','open','open','','2-autosave-v1','','','2014-10-08 02:08:03','2014-10-08 02:08:03','',2,'http://getadora.com/2-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(415,1,'2014-05-30 14:56:17','2014-05-30 14:56:17','','Logo','','inherit','open','open','','logo-2','','','2014-05-30 14:56:17','2014-05-30 14:56:17','',51,'http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Logo.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(424,1,'2014-05-30 16:00:38','2014-05-30 16:00:38','<p style=\"text-align: center;\">In the start-up world we have what would be considered a Dream Team. Click on any of us to learn more.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/BenFaanunuSmall.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-299 size-full\" src=\"http://getadora.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/KyleThomasSmall.jpg\" alt=\"KyleThomasSmall\" widt